title: Giant OD2 50mm stem for Mountain Bike.

description.text:
Some Giant Mountain bikes use the OD2 steerer-tube stem diameter. This is 1.25", or 31.8mm.

Giant sells stems, but they only go down to 60mm. While I have one on order, I got impatient waiting for it, and so designed this to see what 50mm feels like.

Warning: A bike stem is a high-stressed part. This part was made extra thick to be strong, but depending on how you print it, it may break, and that could lead to injury or death. So you have to decide on your own if you are willing to use this. I recommend just buying the real Giant 60mm part for $40. I made this just to try to see what 50mm feels like.

I rode mine no problem:

https://www.strava.com/activities/595607124

Strength depends on printing parameters and orientation.

I printed it in eSUN PET-G with 100% infill. Orient the front plate part sideways as that has good layer strength and will make the most accurate profile for the bars.

I printed the stem itself in the orientation that it sits on the bike. This gives good surface finish to the visible parts, and has a reasonable layer strength orientation.

This requires six 30mm M5 socket-cap screws, six M5 washers, six four M5 nuts.

You may want to glue some sandpaper to a 1.25 inch wood or 3D printed dowel and clean up the surfaces.

title: Malyan M180 Fan Holder
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - Share Alike

description.text:
I started up my new Malyan M180, and the first problem I ran into was when I was about to feed filament. I just couldn’t get it into the extruder. The feeding mechanism could only be behind the fan. I started to dismount it with the result that I lost 1 nut and 1 washer (I did eventually find 1 on the floor and one under the heated plate). I am certainly not the first user to run into this kind of problem. Filament breaks, gets stuck and so on. So one has to be able to reach the feeder in a simpler and faster way. Who wants to dismount the fans when you have preheated the extruder for a filament change, just before you are about to print a new design. I don’t!
My goal was to design a fan holder which allows me to dismount the fan without any tools.
This is the result. One just snaps on the fan.
Instructions:
You will need 8 25 mm M3 bolts.

  • Dismount the nuts and the fan grid. There are no reason to use this grid, it only causes extra noise.
  • Pull the fan out, if you haven’t done it before be careful not to snap the cable to the fan.
  • Loosen the tension on the extruder wheel. The screw in the upper middle is actually the axis for the tension mechanism.
  • Remove the threaded axis, a good idea is to use 2 nuts that are tightened together.
  • Now mount the fan holder with the M3 bolts, these bolts holds the extruder stepper motor so tighten well.
  • And now just snap on the fan and you are ready to go.

From now on any problem behind the fans can be fixed in a second!

If you find my design useful please give me a TIP

comments.text: I found that 30mm screws were too long by about 3mm. I just shortened them with a Dremel. I also left the stud on place that provides the pivot for the idler tensioner. Three screws are plenty to hold the fan bracket and the stud really stabilizes the fan. Either way will work, but I took the easiest route. While I had the fans out, I peeled back the label and gave the shaft a drop of 3-in-1 oil. One of the fans had been slowing down. I will replace them someday, but I want to get some connectors first.

Notes:

Pipe Clip is a springy clip to go on standard ¾” sprinkler pipe, which is
about 1” outside diameter. I use these to keep filament reels in place on
a spool holder made from ¾” sprinkler pipe components.

I printed this in ABS on a Flashforge Creator Pro. The factory file is
included with the files to use directly, if you are using Simplify3d.
Also among the files is the SolidWorks model, which is fully parametric.
The global variables in the SolidWorks file have all aspects of the geometry
to allow modification of the ID, wall thickness, clip height, gap where
there needs to be gaps to allow the clip to function properly, angle of
the tabs, and thickness and length of the tabs.

I don’t know how this will print in PLA – I suspect the sections that
are supposed to be able to move will stick together, but perhaps not.
The basic settings used the print the parts in the photos were:
Layer height: 0.3”
Top/Bottom solid layers: 4
Outside/Periimeter shells: 8
First layer speed: 30%
Brim, 2 layers, 3 outlines, 0.2mm offset from part
No raft
No supports
Infill: 50%, rectilinear, 45 and -45 degrees (but infill never actually
gets used at this size)
Extruder temp: 230C, Platform temp: 105C
Default printing speed: 1500 mm/min

I’m sure this could be printed faster. I went slowly to get that first
layer right, and to help ensure the part would function properly.

description.text:
This is a chit / token holder specifically for Shadows of Brimstone, however it will work in any game with a large number of 30mm and 21mm circular tokens such as most FantasyFlights or Flying Frog games.
One of the trays is meant to hold a combination of the 30mm and 21mm tokens, the other just 21mm tokens. Printed together they are sized to hold the full stack of each type of token from one of the base starter sets from SoB.
If you would like to use the trays as storage in addition to in-game dispensing then print out enough of the caps to use. They stay in place by friction and so a relatively coarse print setting lets the slight striation from the FPM print lock the caps in place.
This was my very first tinkercad design and among my first 3d prints so it is extremely inefficient. There's lots of wasted plastic and some of the base decorations cause the print to take longer to complete than strictly necessary. description.text:
The 2.5D rhino is part of the three layered animal (tla) family. When build from beech plywood it's sturdy enough to be played by children. The birch plywood-version might be admired by adults for the naturalistic side-view and the explicit grain.

When scaling the size should be referenced by the width of a foot.

This build was done on a desktop cnc-machine by Stepcraft from 4 mm poplar plywood using a spiral-toothed 1.2 mm flute as kind of prototype.

A laser cutter might be a good alternative tool to create more rhinos.

Probably you could make a aluminum version and screw the parts together to get tiny key fob.

You can visit Visit https://www.zenziwerken.de/en/Spielsachen/Tiere for more animals.

I searched the web for reference pictures and traced the vectors using Illustrator. Then I build the model in SketchUp to take a look at the design before wasting material.

The circles can be used for alignment and/or as screw-holes.

title: Secret Hitler Portable Print and Play - V2

description.text:
ALL design work and illustrating for the base SVG's for the set was by Grant Pogosyan. Amazing Work!!

Secret Hitler Portable Print and Play V2

Hello!

Secret Hitler is a social deduction game (If you haven't played it...you're missing out!) that was kickstarted. A free print and play version with the rules is available here!

Many of us are making print and play versions until the game is released. Paper sucks. Plastic is awesome. So we designed the entire game to be 3D printed!

This is an epic project for any 3D savvy Secret Hitler fan!

How inspections work

See how there aren't any 3D envelopes? We pass out our membership cards, then after everyone has seen them, we collect them back and place one liberal and one fascist membership card facedown next to the board for the inspection(s)!

What about 5-6 player games?

Now supports 5-6 players! We got requests from multiple people so we decided to update our design!
Unfortunately, our board isn't designed to support 5-6 player games (we don't like them, anyway!). For 7-8 player games, the first slot on the board has an extra square indent and a separate printable STL insert. You should print that the same color as the board, so when you are playing 7-8, you can hide the first inspection icon by placing the insert in the slot. This was edited in the file after we printed and took the pictures seen above, so you will not see it in our images.

Download the zip for all the STL's, and also read the included ReadME file for printing recommendations and tips!

We also got mentioned in a backer update on Secret Hitler's Kickstarter page (as That One Agency, our partnership)! Check out out the article!

If you find any problems in our files, leave a comment, or message us.
Have fun, and make sure to share your makes!

UPDATE 8/5/16:
Reuploaded corrected 7-8 Player toggle stl. It was too big, it wasn't fitting into the slot on the board.

UPDATE 05/10/17:
Now supports 5-7 players as well!! Fascist board was updated to have slots for each power. They can be switched out depending on the amount of players. Simple.

description.text:
The goal of this project was to allow a standard projector to be used for Structured Light Scanning (Like the SLS-1 David Structured Light Scanner) and for light cured 3D resin printers without modifying the printer.  
This design allows the unit to be attached to the bottom mount of the projector and then can be mounted to a tripod.  The lens can be swung out the the way to then watch movies on the big screen.  Because it is adjustable, it will find virtually any sized projector.  
Each lens has its own frame to save fiddling with switching between 1X, 2X or 4X close up lens.  
An updated version of the kit including lens will be available in a variety of colours from our webstore (www.createitforme.com).  
We will also be working on a version that slips onto the end of projectors like the Asus P1 where the lens stands proud of the projector case.  
I would like to acknowledge "pottersfriend" at the David Lasers Laser Scanners forum for concept that lead to this design.
The parts were made using our Projet HD 3000 Plus printer along with a couple of fasteners and a brass bar.

description.text:
This adapter is for the e3d v6 to fit onto a Wanhao Duplicator i3, Cocoon Create, Monoprice Maker Select. It should work on v1, v2 and v2.1

Completely rebuilt but inspired by Piggyjj's model.

This one includes 4 holes for the e3d clamp, i found the original design was making the hotend tilt a bit to the side. Also, it includes 3 prongs to use for the belts instead of the original screw/bolt system. The bolts have problems flexing when the belt is tightened and pulling on them, which works in the metal design, but struggles in the plastic design.

Two versions included, one for a setup with two top x carriages, and one designed for one top x carraige.

I would suggest using this in combination with modified bearing holders, or printed versions to fix the belt rub.

Will require 2x m3 25mm bolts.

The standard long black hex head m3 bolts used in the mk10 extruder can be used in the bottom two holes in the clamp.

With ptfe tube running all the way up to the bottom of the mk10, I have successfully printed ninjaflex (tpu) with this setup.

Print it as it sits, side ovals are for ventilation so motor stays cooler, also saves on some abs.

description.text:
The 'Rocking Smartphone Stand' is a small and easy print that uses very little filament. Using the stand is simple... just slide your Smartphone into the slot and let it rock backwards until it establishes it's balance point. Tap it and it will rock back and forth... very cool, fun, minimalist design that everyone likes. Well worth the time to print one for yourself or as a small gift.

Please note that all phone makes / models have different centres of mass /points of balance so, while this should work for most Smartphones, this may not work with every make / model. It is designed for use with common 4.5" to 5" screen models, not larger phones (Fablets)

The design was originally made to suit a Samsung Galaxy S5 (which works really well). It has also been tested on several iPhone models, which also work fine,... but please be aware that even covers make a difference to the balance point. If this doesn't 'rock your phone' when you first islide your phone in you can adjust the curve of the stand to suit your phones point of balance. You can do this easily with PLA prints... read on for instructions.

Different make / model Smartphones have different depths (thickness). Covers add to the depth so a range of stl's has been provided to ensure a snug fit to hold your phone well so it stays in place as it rocks but is also easy to slide in / out. The range covers phones from 8mm to 13mm thick in 1mm increments.

Although this should work fine (at the designed in angles) for most Smartphones) if your Smartphone wants to fall forward when you slide it in you need to adjust the centre of mass / balancing point. Adjusting the balance point is easy and can be done quickly and easily (with PLA prints) using the following simple process:

(1) Fill a bowl with near boiling water

(2) Drop the stand in for a few seconds then carefully remove it... it will be hot and very easy to bend so take care not to distort it in a way you don't want

(3) Gently bend the stand to make the adjustment you think necessary... and a small adjustment can have a significant affect. As you can adjust it repeatedly until you get it right, it's better to make small / careful adjustments at a time until you get it dialled in to rock.

(4) Let it cool in the adjusted shape... you can run it under cold water to speed up the process. It will return to its original fully hardened state.

(5) Test your Smartphone and see how the rocking action has changed

(6) It may take a few attempts to get it balancing and rocking well. If you have distorted the stand during the adjustment process print another (...as they are small prints that don't use much filament) and match the 'prototype' with the adjustment made in one go so you end up with a nice looking Smartphone stand that rocks!

Again, this should not be necessary in most instances but if it is making the necessary adjustment is not difficult at all... give it a go as the result is well worth the time and effort.
Charging: If you want to plug your phone in to charge while it's on the stand just slide it in upside down with the charging cable attached out the top. It won't rock as usual, because it is effectively tethered, but still usable as a stand.

Please refer to the print settings and images for additional information and instructions.

Note: If you like this check out the rest of my fun and practical designs... and post photos of your prints with the make / model noted for other members reference.

description.text:
We've all done it. You're cruising your favorite internet dumping ground(tumblr, reddit, 4chan...whoever that guy is), and you saw IT. That one thing that burned into your very soul like a drunken tattoo from a blind guy. You saw it when you went to work, then you saw it when you closed your eyes at night. It haunted you like a disembodied spirit un-anchored from the web to follow you until you broke down and could no longer take it.

.....This button will fix all of that!

Now, you can just "unsee" all of that horrible stuff. Whether it was those girls that were doing that thing with the pasta, or that guy who had that strange scar with that....ugh never mind. You know what I'm talking about. The internet is the perfect example of why our species can't have nice things.

How to use:

Simply print out this button in the heaviest material you can find. If Shapeways starts offering lead as one of their materials, you can bet this will be the first thing they print.Barring that, you can maybe use one of those newfangled metal-filled PLA filaments all the kids are raving about.

  1. Print out in heavy material. The heavier the better. Maybe even cast it out of ceremonial bronze.
  2. (this step requires some assistance from a friend) hand the button to your friend.

description.text:
Update 23/7/2017: An update on the case that support camera and GPIO is here. Try it if you have problem to print the hinge of the original version.

Update 14/3/2017: It is quite sad to receiving some of your comments reporting parts fused together, but at the same time some other telling me they have no problem at all. I believe it all depends on how well your printer handle hanging and small gaps. The geometry of the hinge is really compact. Otherwise it will not go well with the baby Pi Zero and Pi Zero W.
Good news for those who had tried with problem. I added a "v2" version for the low profile case. I added extra clearance to the hinge geometry. Hopefully it would avoid parts fusing together when print with bigger nozzle size. If it works for your please post a make picture back to here. I really want to see if it works (or not). Thanks.

Update 13/2/2017: I received comments suggested me to separate to model to 2 parts since the top and bottom fused together as it print. I have no idea if one can really assemble it if you print them separately, but I did it anyway and let you guys to have a try. Let me knows if it helps.

Update 2: The GPIO version is here. To fix the Pi Zero you'll need 4 x M2.6 screws that are 15mm long.

Update: The camera version is here! It hold both your Pi Zero and Camera together in a small box. It comes in 2 sub-versions. First one doesn't use any screw, but you may need some extra help to secure the Pi Zero in the position it suppose to be. In my case I use 2 rubber bands. The second one use 4 x M2.6 screws which are 12mm long.

My first Raspberry Pi Zero case. Support the new version that comes with a camera port. It can be printed in one piece and no assembly is required. This is a low profile version, which means it will only hold the PI Zero itself without any jumper and HAT on it. I'll publish more version later. So do follow this creation if you need bigger versions that can hold the GPIO jumpers, camera or even HAT.

  • First I used http://boxmaker.rahulbotics.com/ to make a 4.5 x 4.5 inch cube
  • After that I made a trace of the slimes face and put it on one of the faces of the box
  • On the base of the block I added a small slot so that I could later on add the Slime ball.
  • For the slime ball I just traced it in illustrator then copied the stroke and made a small border for it
  • I also added a small piece to the slime ball to fit into the slot
  • the settings I used were 300 resolution, with raster speed at 100, raster power at 60, vector speed at 9, vector power at 100 and vector frequency at 5000
  • To assemble it I slid the slime ball into the slot I made at the base and stared from there. After that I tried to see which pieces fit where and when they fit I used acrylic glue to hold them together.

title: Modular Open-air NAS with Stackable 3.5 SATA HDD Caddies

description.text:
1. History

About 7 years ago I out grew my Media Server Case.

I didn't want to purchase a specific NAS, like a QNAP or Synology, or buy a big gamer type case. So, I built one out of two pieces of MDF, aluminium strips and some other small scrap wood.

All screwed together. 7 years it is still going strong running 10 SATA Drives, but I wanted to modernise. (3d print a new "modular" case).

The goal is if I want another HDD, I print another caddy. If I use a different motherboard, I can adapt the jigsaw pieces to fit it.

2. The New Server

This `Modular NAS Server thing`` is the dumping ground of what I am creating.

What have I made so far ?

  • [X] 2.1 - Stackable (modular) HDD Caddies
  • [ ] Rack Mounted (I have a server cabinet) (not yet done)
  • [ ] ATX Motherboard Mount
  • [ ] PSU Mount
  • [ ] Rack Mount Adaptors and Other Supports

2.1 Stackable (modular) HDD Caddies

As the photo shows, I have printed my first 3 caddies.(Yellow was the first "new" version)

I wanted them to be "put together" with minimal screws. The puzzle pieces will come into play later when I make it rack mount able. For now, it is just stackable.

It is not perfect, but is meeting my need.

2.1.1 HDD Caddies - Yet to make

  • Doors
  • SATA BackPlane
  • Rear Cooling Ducting

remixed_from.author: jamesarm97
remixed_from.title: Thumbwheel M3 with scale 0.01 mm with grip (Nut on bottom)

description.text:
I tried to print the ThumbwheelM3 from Jamesam97 but couldn't fit any M3 nuts in them, so I adapted his design and changed it a little bit, because i didnt like the number scale and the grip (the grip looks great, but didn't give me a good feeling).

For the grip I used a parametric Gearwheel (module =1 teeth = 22) file i made. I added a pocket for the nut and curved arrows to show the direction in order to either lower (-) or raise (+) the printing table.

After printing I needed to clean and chamfer the pocket a Little bit. Then I put the Thumbwheel on a table, put a nut in the pocket and pressed it by using the flat side of a hammer. Any other flat and solid item should serve well in order to press the nut in.

ATTENTION: also put something solid on the table, otherwise you could leave marks!

The grip on these wheels is fantastic, but I will Need to add a Little rubber ring underneath the head of the screw to increase the friction. Right now the spring is not putting enough force on them to hold them in place.

I also tried to print one out with the nut-pocket on the upside and use Support structure, but it only messed up the bottom side. So i recommend to put the nut-pocket on the bottom side, to generate a G-Code.

(the thumbwheel mounted is printed with reduced speed, the other one is printed with standard settings. Software for generating G-Code is Cura)
